Sure! Here's an example program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int countWordOccurrences(const std::string& filename, const std::string& word) {
    std::ifstream inputFile(filename);
    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    while (getline(inputFile, line)) {
        size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = line.find(word, pos)) != std::string::npos) {
            count++;
            pos += word.length();
        }
    }

    inputFile.close();
    return count;
}

int main() {
    std::string filename, word;
    std::cout << "Enter the filename: ";
    std::cin >> filename;
    std::cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    std::cin >> word;

    int count = countWordOccurrences(filename, word);
    std::cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" occurs " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, the `countWordOccurrences` function takes two parameters: the `filename` of the text file to read, and the `word` to count occurrences of. It opens the file, reads it line by line, and uses the `find` function to search for occurrences of the word in each line. It increments the `count` variable for each occurrence of the word. Finally, it returns the total count.

The `main` function prompts the user to enter the filename and word, then calls the `countWordOccurrences` function to get the count. It then displays the count to the user.

You can compile and run this program, and it will read the specified text file and count the occurrences of the specified word.

